>>A bind mount maps a real host directly into a container 

host path
↓
mounted into container path

>>Difference from volume:

volume     → Docker-managed storage
bind mount → direct host path mapping

>>Creating a Host Directory

On the host:

mkdir -p ~/binddemo
echo "hello from host" > ~/binddemo/file.txt
cat ~/binddemo/file.txt

This creates data on the host system.

>>Mounting Host Directory into Container

Run conatainer with bind mount:

docker run -it --name bindtest -v ~/binddemo:/data ubuntu bash


Inside container :

ls /data
cat /data/file.txt

This proves the cotainer can read files directly from the host directory.

>>Writing from container to host

Inside the container:

echo "written from container" > /data/from_container.txt
cat /data/from_container.txt
exit

on the host:

ls ~/binddemo
cat ~/binddemo/from_container.txt

This proves files created inside the container appear directly on the host.

>>Live sync behaviour:

Run container again:

docker run -it --name bindlive -v ~/binddemo:/data ubuntu bash

Inside container:

cat /data/file.txt

from another host terminal:

echo "host changed this" > ~/binddemo/file.txt
cat ~/binddemo/file.txt


Back inside container:

cat /data/file.txt
This proves bind mounts reflect live changes immediately.

Removing Container Does Not Remove Host Files

Remove container:

docker rm = -f bindlive

Verify on host:

ls ~/binddemo
cat ~/binddemo/file.txt
cat ~/binddemo/from_container.txt

Result:
host file remain unchanged.

This proves bind-mounted data belongs to the host path, not to the container lifecylce.

>>Key concept:
bind mount = direct live mapping of host files into container

>>Use cases:

local development
config files
source code sharing















